Catalytic oxidation is influenced by various factors like temperature and pH of the reaction medium along with the morphology, surface charge properties, density of adsorption sites and surface-volume ratio of the nano/microstructured materials. The surface charge properties of the metallic nanoparticles can be easily engineered by using a suitable capping agent and the methodology of synthesis. Positively and negatively charged Au nanoparticles have been prepared by using cysteamine and citrates as capping agents, respectively. The catalytic oxidation of TMB was much faster in the acidic medium than the neutral and basic medium by cysteamine capped positively charged Au nanoparticles. Actually, in the acidic medium, the –NH2 functional groups of the cysteamine are protonated to –NH3
                     + groups which ensured greater stability of the Au nanoparticle (Fig. 3
                     ).

Liu et al. [61] cross-linked catalytic heme-redox active sites onto melamine (MA) through 1-(3-Dimethylaminopropyl)-3-ethyl carbodiimide (EDC) cross-linker for the mineralization of Au–Ag bimetallic rod-like nanocomposites (MA-Hem/Au–Ag) and subsequently analyzed its peroxidase-like activities for the oxidation of TMB. In comparison, the catalytic activity of MA-Hem/Au–Ag polymer matrix for the oxidation of TMB was much better than hemin and MA. It was attributed to the presence of amine and carboxyl functional groups which provide additional electronic pathways towards the catalysis-active sites and the “silver effect”. Chen et al. [62] synthesized Pt-loaded hollow mesoporous carbon nanospheres. The monodispersed carbon nanospheres with a huge hollow cavity and mesoporous carbon skeleton were prepared through high-temperature carbonization and NaOH etching of core-shell structured SiO2@RF/SiO2 (RF = resorcinol–formaldehyde resin) nanospheres. Pt nanoparticles with a diameter of 1–3 nm were incorporated on the hollow mesoporous carbon nanospheres through a surface graft of −NH2 groups (Fig. 5
                        ). The synthesized Pt-loaded hollow mesoporous carbon nanospheres nanocomposites exhibited superior peroxidase-like catalytic activity toward the oxidation of TMB. The glucose sensing parameters for various noble metal-based colorimetric sensors are given in Table 1
                        .

However, it has been found that pristine CeO2 is not capable of catalyzing the surface redox reactions effectively and hence is seldom used in biosensors applications. Therefore, nano-/microstructured CeO2 is used in combination with other electrocatalytic materials having excellent electronic conductivity and faster electron-transfer abilities. Materials such as TiO2 [70], NiO [102], Co3O4 [103], CoO [104], Zeolite-Y [105], montmorillonite [106], porphyrins [107,108], etc. have been used as filler/support or synergic materials for CeO2 for the fabrication of efficient colorimetric biosensor. Zhao et al. [70] designed nanocomposites comprising highly dispersed CeO2 on TiO2 nanotubes (molar ratio of Ce/Ti = 0.1), which showed excellent peroxidase-like activities which were also higher than those of CeO2/nanowire-TiO2, CeO2/nanorod-TiO2, and CeO2/nanoparticle-TiO2 (Fig. 8
                            (a)). The linear dynamic range and LOD for CeO2/nanotubes-TiO2 nanocomposites toward glucose were 10–500 μM and 6.1 μM, respectively. Co3O4 nanoparticles show peroxidase-like ability due to electron transfer between the substrate and H2O2 instead of OH• radicals [109]. Co3O4-CeO2 nanosheets prepared by a wet-chemical deposition precipitation method were used for the fabrication of an integrated paper-based analytical device to detected glucose. The peroxidase-like activities of Co3O4-CeO2 nanosheets were tested for the oxidation of colorless TMB to the blue-colored oxidized form of TMB in the presence of H2O2. A linear dynamic range of 0.005–1.5 mM and a detection limit of 0.21 μM were analyzed through a smartphone [103]. Highly ordered mesoporous CoO/CeO2 catalyst exhibited excellent peroxidase mimic activity toward oxidation of TMB (Fig. 8 (b)). Colorimetric assays showed detection limits of 0.88 and 19.6 μM for H2O2 and glucose, respectively. The promising catalytic behavior was ascribed to its interconnected large mesopores, highly dense surface defects and oxygen vacancies introduced by the heterojunction interface nanocrystals of CeO2 and CoO within pore walls [104]. Synergistic effect of highly dispersed CeO2 nanoparticles with 5–10 nm sizes supported on zeolite Y with a surface area of 517 m2 g−1 and pore volume 0.329 cm3 g−1) was also explored for analyzing the peroxidase-mimicking behavior for the detection of H2O2 and glucose [105] (Table 3
                           ).
